      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">The different styles tend to work the best if you apply them to a whole document, but they can be set on a per cell basis if you want.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>The "grid" style is best for editing, as it shows most clearly where you can insert new data.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>"bubbles" work best if you assign individual cell background colors. If you leave all cells the same color, TreeSheets automatically chooses alternate colors to avoid bubbles becoming invisible.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>The "lines" style is nice for mindmap style documents.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    <td style="font-weight: bold;">Images &amp; Styles
      <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 11pt;">
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Add Images to cells to make your document clearer. Images appear in front of the text of that cell. Put an image in its own cell for maximum flexibility. Try adding a (small) image to any cell above (menu Edit/Add Image, or pick one from the image drop down on the toolbar).
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>Images are stored inside a document (.cts) file, meaning if you move a file around, you will never lose the images. If you use an image multiple times in a document, only one copy is stored.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>If you'd like to refer to large images in a treesheet, and they would be too clumsy to have inside the sheet, you can also simply put the images in the same folder as the .cts, and simply put just their name in a cell. You can then use Edit/Open File (F4) to view them.
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>You can refer to any file type this way
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
          <td>to conveniently add new file links, just drag and drop non-image files onto cells
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-style: italic;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Make a cell bold, or italic, or both! Try CTRL+b or CTRL+i on some cells, both are toggles. Additionally, typewriter and underlined style are available from the Edit/Text Style menu.
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;"><span style="text-decoration: line-through;">strikethrough (CTRL+t) is a useful style for TODO lists to indicate items that have been processed but you don't want to delete yet.</span>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Try coloring cells with the two color selectors in the toolbar. You can double-click on the current colors to set them instantly. Select cell(s) that contain grid(s) and use the border color drop down, or Edit/Set Border Width menu to change their look.
      </td>
      </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
    <td style="font-weight: bold;">Search &amp; Navigation
      <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 11pt;">
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">You can use instant search by typing something in the search box in the toolbar (CTRL+f to focus on this box). Any matching cells will be highlighted (F3 to cycle through the results). Type something in the replace box, and then use one of the two replace operations in the search menu.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>As an alternative to search, "go to matching cell" (F6) cycles through the cells that have the same text as the current cell, which can be useful as a cross reference or a linking mechanism. It has preference for going to a cell with different formatting, meaning you can use formatting as a way to distinguish definition cells from link cells. Try it:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>CycleCell
          </td>
          <td>...
          </td>
          <td>CycleCell
          </td>
          <td>CycleCell
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
          <td style="font-weight: bold;">LinkRef
          </td>
          <td>...
          </td>
          <td style="font-style: italic;">LinkRef
          </td>
          <td style="font-style: italic;">LinkRef
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
          <td>Definition
          </td>
          <td>
          </td>
          <td>Use
          </td>
          <td>Use
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Store urls or collections of bookmarks inside TreeSheets, and simply press F5 to open any of them in your browser
      </td>
      </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    <td style="font-weight: bold;">Tags &amp; Hierarchy
      <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 11pt;">
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Tags are a good way to deal with words that you use repeatedly in a sheet, like statuses, categories etc. To make something a tag, find an occurrence, and do "Add Cell as Tag" (Edit/Tag... menu). From now on, you can set any other cell to a tag with CTRL+Right Mouse Button (popup menu). Tags are colored blue, to signal to you it is a tag. This helps spotting if a tag is mistyped.
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">A powerful operation that works well with tags is "Hierarchy Swap". An Example of what it does:
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>The motivation behind Hierarchy Swap is that you use TreeSheets to organize your data in tree format, but often, trees are not ideal to organize data, because they force you to make choices about what subdivision is most important. 
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Say that I am organizing a project, and I am trying to keep track of what tasks it involves. I am using tags to indicate the people that work on it, the deliverables, and the topic areas:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>milestone 1
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>front end
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>fred
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>fix the GUI
                </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                <td>connect to database
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
              <td>bob
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>overhaul graphics
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>back end
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>fred
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>add input forms
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
          <td>milestone 2
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>back end
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>fred
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>set up new tables
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
              <td>bob
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>buy new servers
                </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                <td>set up networking
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Notice how in the above table, milestones are the most important subdivision, the topic areas second, and people the least important. This a pretty arbitrary choice, we might want to see things from a people perspective, and now with Hierarchy Swap you can! Select any occurrence of "fred", and press F8 twice, and you'll get this:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>fred
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>milestone 1
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>front end
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
