                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
          <td>bob
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>milestone 1
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>front end
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>overhaul graphics
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>milestone 2
              <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 7pt;">
              <tr>
              <td>back end
                <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 6pt;">
                <tr>
                <td>buy new servers
                </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                <td>set up networking
                </td>
                </tr>
                </table>
              </td>
              </tr>
              </table>
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Effectively what you've done is saying: "show me this hierarchy from fred's perspective". You can now see exactly what he works on. You could do the same for bob, if needed. If you want to see what fred is doing on the back end, press F8 just once on "back end" (within fred), and you have tweaked your perspective yet again. Press once more, and now front/back end becomes the major subdivision.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Keep pressing F8 on various tags, to see how you can attain any perspective you need.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Important to note is how on any swap, the tag that was previously the parent, now becomes the child of the selected tag. This means that it doesn't matter how often you do this swap, no information is lost. It means that you should be able to get the tree back in its original configuration if you wanted to.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>So you can see this feature as allowing you to have snippets of information which can have any number of tags associated with them. The Hierarchy Swap allows you to determine the current order of importancy of tags, and thus, the tree view is nothing but the most recent view
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>You can still keep editing data to this tree whatever "view" it is in, no need to reset the tree to its original order. Trees like this have no set order!
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Note how promoting "fred" doesn't automatically promote "bob". TreeSheets doesn't know that these tags are of the same "type". Not all uses of tags have clear cut types, and its not always necessary to reorder all at once, so this keeps the feature simple.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Related to working with Hierarchies, is the ability to "Flatten" a hierarchy. Take the milestone example above, and after applying Flatten, you get
