      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">While not as useful as the hierarchical version for editing and seeing structure, it is the only way to export this data to "flat" programs like spreadsheets (see Export/CSV). Spreadsheet users like to model data this way, so the reverse operation, "Hierarchify", allows you take such a table and turn it back into the hierarchy above.
      </td>
      </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
    <td style="font-weight: bold;">Advanced operations
      <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 11pt;">
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">(25) if a cell has no text but it does have a grid, such as the cells below, it is rendered without space for the text. This may make it difficult to select, to be able to insert text. You can select any cell by simply pressing ESC when you have selected a sub-cell (try selecting (26), then ESC, then type some text). Also convenient, double clicking on a grid line selects the entire grid. Try this by double clicking between (26) and (27), then type some text.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>this
          </td>
          <td>grid
          </td>
          <td>has
          </td>
          <td>no
          </td>
          <td>text
          </td>
          <td>header
          </td>
          <td>(26)
          </td>
          <td>(27)
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Transposing is a useful operation if you're trying to rearange lists to get a more manageable layout. Select this cell, and Edit/Grid Reorganization/Transpose a few times. Make sure you have it showing vertically, and then additionally try Edit/Grid Reorganization/Sort after selecting either the first or second column.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">One
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">Two
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">Three
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">Four
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">Five
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">1
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">2
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">3
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">4
        </td>
        <td style="background-color: #FFFF80;color: #800000;">5
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Have a look at the many import and export options, or print to paper or pdf
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">The "Wrap in parent" (F9) operation is a great way to create new hierarchy. Make any selection of cells, and this operation will make those into a new grid, and a new parent that sits in the place of where the cells came from. For example, try selecting C &amp; D below, then press F9, and type something:
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>A
        </td>
        <td>B
        </td>
        <td>C
        </td>
        <td>D
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Filters are a feature that is useful once your treesheets grow really big. They allow you to temporarily filter out a subset of the sheet to focus on the cells you're looking for. This works by forcing the cells that are filtered out to be displayed as 1-pixel text, and in light grey. Try out the filtering options in the view menu:
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>Try entering "treesheets" as search query right now. some cells will look red. Now try setting the search filter (View -&gt; Filter -&gt; Show only cells in current search), all the sheet should shrink considerably, making it easier to see what you're looking for. Do this at the top level view of this sheet. Try zooming in and out with the filter on. Try editing the search query, the filter view will change as you type.
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Try the "last 10% of edits" on this sheet, too. Make sure to turn the search query off, first. Note that if you have documents from older versions of treesheets, this feature may not show the edits that you expect, since those versions did not keep track of the last edit time of each cell yet.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">If you're on an older computer, or work with really big sheets, try the option "fast line rendering" to get a sheet which is less pretty, but scrolls faster.
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">TreeSheets is great for presentations. Unlike traditional tools like powerpoint, which make it really difficult to convey a sense of structure to the audience, you can organize a treesheet as if your entire presentation was a single "slide", and have minimized sub-slides that you can zoom into. To help its use as a presentation tool, TreeSheets has two viewing options: Fullscreen View (F11) to reduce visual clutter, and Scaled View (F12) which tries to make the current view as large as possible.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>Note, both this feature and printing make use of a scaling method that does not preserve rendering fidelity in all cases. This will be fixed in a future version.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">TreeSheets has a built-in scripting language for creating plugins
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>These scripts are placed in the "scripts/" folder, and are automatically added to the "Scripts" menu at the start of TreeSheets, from where they can be started
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Scripts can read and modify all of the current TreeSheet!
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Scripts are written in The Lobster Programming language
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>Read more about the language:
          </td>
          <td>http://strlen.com/lobster/
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>The functions you can use in your script are listed in docs/script_reference.html
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>The ones that start with ts_ are specific to TreeSheets, the others are general language functions
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Read the existing scripts to get an idea what they can do!
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">TreeSheets also contains a novel spreadsheet like programming language that is not fully functional yet.
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>It works by putting operations right inside grids, mixed with data
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>the language then evaluates grids as an expression from left to right (and top to bottom) once you "run" the sheet. Select Program/Run (or the toolbar button) and the green square below should be filled with a 9 (not 7!) 
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>1
          </td>
          <td>+
          </td>
          <td>2
          </td>
          <td>*
          </td>
          <td>3
          </td>
          <td>
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>You create the program by giving certain cells special meaning. By default, all cells are white (data). From the Program/Mark As menu you can make them operations (pink), or view cells (light green). A view cell simply shows the current value of any operation before it. In the grid below, try marking the + as an operation, and the last empty cell as horizontal view using the program menu, then pressing run:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>1
          </td>
          <td>+
          </td>
          <td>2
          </td>
          <td>
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Operations automatically work on whole grids, for example:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>1
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>2
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>3
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          <td>+
          </td>
          <td>
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>4
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>5
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>6
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          <td>*
          </td>
          <td>
            <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 8pt;">
            <tr>
            <td>7
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>8
            </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>9
            </td>
            </tr>
            </table>
          </td>
          <td>
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>It is not recommended at this stage to actually use the language unless you're very adventurous, as only few operations are implemented, and many combinations of operands are not supported. Sort of working:
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>+
          </td>
          <td>-
          </td>
          <td>*
          </td>
          <td>/
          </td>
          <td>&lt;
          </td>
          <td>&gt;
          </td>
          <td>&lt;=
          </td>
          <td>&gt;=
          </td>
          <td>==
          </td>
          <td>!=
          </td>
          <td>=
          </td>
          <td>&lt;&gt;
          </td>
          <td>inc
          </td>
          <td>dec
          </td>
          <td>neg
          </td>
          <td>sum
          </td>
          <td>transpose
          </td>
          <td>if
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>For more details on operations, see Help &gt; Load operation reference (CTRL+ALT+F1).
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Have a look at the sales.cts example to see what it can do.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">If you work on TreeSheets files on multiple computers, store them in a shared folder (such as DropBox) and turn on Options -&gt; Auto reload documents
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>This way, you will always be up to date on all your machines when you save the document
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td style="font-weight: normal;background-color: #FFFFFF;">Running TreeSheets from the command line
        <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 10pt;">
        <tr>
        <td>You can run TreeSheets from the command line
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>as arguments, you may specify a single file to load
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>If TreeSheets is already running in the system, this will cause it to pass the file to the existing instance, then quit
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>you may also run it with -p as an argument
          <table style="border-width: 2pt; font-size: 9pt;">
          <tr>
          <td>This starts TreeSheets in "portable" mode, where (on Windows) it writes settings to a .ini file in the current directory rather than to the registry
          </td>
          </tr>
          </table>
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>Note that to run correctly from the command line, at least on Windows, TreeSheets.exe needs to be started with a full path, otherwise it will not be able to find its icons etc. relative to the executable path.
        </td>
        </tr>
        </table>
      </td>
      </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
    </tr>
    </table>
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
